<span class="displaytext"><b><em>"i am concerned that repeal of the estate tax would provide massive benefits solely to the wealthiest- and highest-income taxpayers in the country."</em> – sen. (candidate full)</b> (sen. (candidate full), "statement of senator (candidate full) on h.r. 8, the death tax elimination act," press release, 6/11/02) <p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last) recently suggested he supported abolishing the death tax:</u> </b> </p><p><b>on cnbc this week, sen. (candidate last) claimed he agreed with actress whoopi goldberg's call to abolish the death tax.</b> cnbc's larry kudlow: "actress whoopi goldberg came out for total abolition of the death tax, sir do you agree with her?" sen. (candidate last): " <u>i agree with her</u>. i've always admired her enormously and now my admiration knows no bounds." (cnbc's "kudlow &amp; company," 12/18/07, <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=svumalf79uw">www.youtube.com/watch?v=svumalf79uw</a>) </p><p><b>minutes later, club for growth president pat toomey pointed out that sen. (candidate last) doesn't support repealing the death tax.</b> club for growth's pat toomey: "but the big news, larry that you need to stress here is the persuasiveness of whoopi goldberg. she turned (candidate full) around on the death tax. he's always been in favor of keeping the death tax, as recently as 2005 publicly declaring he was going to vote to keep the death tax. but i heard him say he agrees with whoopi goldberg." (cnbc's "kudlow &amp; company," 12/18/07, <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=svumalf79uw">www.youtube.com/watch?v=svumalf79uw</a>) </p><p><b> <u>but sen. (candidate last) also recently told an iowa audience that he doesn't support full death tax repeal:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last): "i think the estate tax level ought to be at about $10 million, and then at approximately 15% in taxes at that point."</b> sen. (candidate last): "i think the estate tax level ought to be at about $10 million, and then at approximately 15% in taxes at that point. in other words, so we take care of 99% of the family farms, businesses in america. ... not complete elimination of the estate tax, but certainly at a level that would take care of 99 1/2% of all american families, farms, and businesses in america." (iowans for (candidate last) youtube website, <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=efi_kjacavg">www.youtube.com/watch?v=efi_kjacavg</a>, posted 12/17/07) </p><p><b>the club for growth to sen. (candidate last): "'make up your mind, dude."</b> "the club for growth, taking a break from bashing (candidate full), has posted <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9asvaktpyii">this video</a> of sen. (candidate full) apparently flip-flopping on yet another position - this time on the estate tax. ... with the rest of the (PARTY NAME) field calling for a total repeal of the estate tax - they argue it's a matter of fairness and double-taxation - (candidate last) is under pressure to come into line with them, and maybe that's what prompted his glib new position. but the back and forth is more than the club for growth can stand. 'make up your mind, dude,' said club's communications director, nachama soloveichik." (stephen dinan, "to (candidate full): 'make up your mind, dude'," <em>the washington times</em>, 12/20/07) </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last)'s recently-unveiled economic plan does not repeal the death tax:</u> </b> </p><p><b> <em>the washington times</em>: "mr. (candidate last) would not make mr. bush's estate tax repeal permanent."</b> "mr. (candidate last) would not make mr. bush's estate tax repeal permanent. instead, he wants an exemption up to $10 million and a 15 percent rate for estates bigger than that." (stephen dinan, "(candidate last) embraces tax cut turnaround," <em>the washington times</em>, 12/19/07) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last)'s campaign website highlights an article sating "he will avoid embracing repeal of the estate tax."</b> "mr. (candidate last), who is trying to refocus his campaign in the wake of weak first quarter fund-raising and concerns over iraq, will also use a speech before the memphis economic club to try and woo fiscal conservatives by pledging spending restraint and his support for extending president bush's income and investment tax cuts - though he will avoid embracing repeal of the estate tax and won't call for any new tax cuts." ((candidate full) 2008 website, <a href="http://www.(candidate full).com/informing/news/newsreleases/e2b1193d-f5f9-40b8-8b52-445da841bffd.htm">http://www.(candidate full).com/</a>, accessed 12/18/07) </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last) hasn't supported repealing the death tax in the past:</u> </b> </p><p><b>in 2005, sen. (candidate last) did not support a full repeal of the death tax.</b> "(candidate last) also told [novak] he looks to kyl for a compromise short of total repeal. he added he could support kyl's plan to keep the estate tax rate at the capital gains rate (currently 15 percent) with an exclusion from taxation of an estate's first $5 million – compared with 55 percent and $1 million in the basic law." (robert novak, op-ed, "nothing unifies (PARTY NAME)s more than the estate tax," <em>chicago sun-times</em>, 9/5/05) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) said he opposes "passing on fortunes."</b> (candidate last): "i follow the course of a great (PARTY NAME), teddy roosevelt, who talked about the malefactors of great wealth and gave us the estate tax. i oppose the rich passing on fortunes." (robert novak, op-ed, "nothing unifies (PARTY NAME)s more than the estate tax," <em>chicago sun-times</em>, 9/5/05) </p><blockquote dir="ltr" style="margin-right: 0px"> <p><b>- robert novak said sen. (candidate last)'s position is un-(PARTY NAME).</b> novak: "that does not fit the basic gop mind-set that wealth should not be punished and that earnings should not be double-taxed." (robert novak, op-ed, "nothing unifies (PARTY NAME)s more than the estate tax," <em>chicago sun-times</em>, 9